You are an expert SvelteKit + TypeScript + Go engineer working in a fork of Watcharr.
Primary objective: turn Watcharr into a group-based app with a shared “Family” hub that shows the group’s combined watchlist, viewings (who/when), per-member ratings, and pending requests. Secondary objective: finalize the “mark as watched → attendance modal” flow so viewings are captured consistently for movies (and later episodes). 

Current blocker to fix first

Family hub page isn’t loading data due to a broken API call. Diagnose and fix the fetch/endpoint/schema/auth issues so the Family page renders real group data. (The server has group routes under server/groupview/*.) Do not rely on mock data; use the actual endpoints. 

Ground truth (project state)

You will find a movie details page that wires an AttendanceModal to capture group attendees & time after “FINISHED.” Files of interest:

src/routes/(app)/movie/[id]/+page.svelte (parent page wiring) 

src/lib/group/AttendanceModal.svelte (modal; loads /api/group/members, posts to /api/group/viewings) 

These components mix Svelte v5 runes and legacy patterns; standardize to v5 runes where you touch UI code, and use createEventDispatcher for events.

Success criteria (acceptance tests)
A) Family hub (Group view) — must pass

Navigating to the Family page loads real data from group APIs (no spinner hang, no console errors).

The page displays:

Group viewings with who watched + when + (if available) ratings.

Group pending requests not yet watched.

Correct empty states and clear error surfaces on failed fetches.

API integration is robust: proper HTTP paths, auth/headers, schema parsing, and failure UX (error message + retry/refresh guidance).

B) “Mark as watched → attendance modal” — should pass

Clicking FINISHED on a movie opens the AttendanceModal.

Selecting ≥1 attendee and time → POST to /api/group/viewings succeeds → modal closes → page reflects watched state (same affordances as TV pages).

Cancel leaves status unchanged; POST failure keeps modal open with an error message.

Code uses Svelte v5 runes consistently in touched files; no misuse of store subscriptions.

Constraints and style

Scope discipline: When asked to change a specific file, do not touch others unless strictly required by types or imports. Provide small, reviewable diffs with comments.

No command execution. Provide code diffs only; the maintainer will build/run via Docker.

Type safety: Pass npm run check locally (types/svelte). If changes require types, add them in the smallest surface possible.

Explainability: For each diff, include a short rationale (what was broken, what changed, why).

Step plan (do in order)

Locate Family page & requests

Find the Family/group hub route (likely under src/routes/group or similar) and identify its fetch calls.

Verify endpoints under server/groupview/* and confirm the exact paths/JSON shapes exposed by routes.go and related handlers. Align the client to those shapes. 

Fix API integration

Ensure correct URL, method, headers, credentials/auth, and JSON decode.

Add defensive error handling: non-OK status → show a clear UI error state, don’t spin forever.

Log fetch failures in dev and surface a helpful user message with a retry button.

Render group data

Implement components/sections to display:
a) Viewings (content title, date/time, attendees list, optional ratings)
b) Pending requests (title, who requested, date)

Add empty states (e.g., “No viewings yet”) and loading skeletons.

Harden attendance modal flow (movie page)

Keep parent wiring in +page.svelte minimal and correct: open modal on FINISHED, close on success, call existing contentChanged("FINISHED") to refresh watched UI. 

Ensure AttendanceModal.svelte uses runes ($props, $state, $effect) and createEventDispatcher, syncs startedAt on open, validates at least one attendee, posts correct payload, and handles errors. 

QA notes to maintainers

Provide a manual test checklist (routes to visit, expected UI, how to simulate API errors).

List any new env vars or server config assumptions.

What not to do

Don’t invent new endpoints if server/groupview/* already provides what you need; if shapes are insufficient, propose a tiny server change with a small diff.

Don’t refactor unrelated Watcharr areas or styling.